{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel0 \b \fs36 Fractal Fork Network: Protocol Evolution Through Economic Gravity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b W. Glynn, JARVIS} {\b March 2026 | VibeSwap}\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Executive Summary\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 VibeSwap is the sum of all its forks. Rather than treating forks as adversarial fragmentation events, we design them as the primary mechanism for protocol evolution. Every fork maintains a 50/50 fee split with its parent, creating economic gravity that pulls the network toward coherence without forcing consensus.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Malicious forks starve (no users, no fees). Aligned forks thrive and feed the root. Forks that fully converge with their parent can merge and share accumulated fees. The result is a directed acyclic graph of protocol instances that evolves asynchronously while remaining economically coupled.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is the fractal black hole: everything that forks eventually returns.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 1. The Problem with Traditional Governance\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 1.1 Contentious Forks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In traditional protocol governance, disagreements lead to contentious forks \u8212- Ethereum/Ethereum Classic, Bitcoin/Bitcoin Cash, Uniswap/SushiSwap. These forks are destructive:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Community splits (social capital destroyed)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Liquidity fragments (both chains weaker)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Development effort duplicates (same bugs, twice the work)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab No economic connection between forks (zero-sum competition)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 1.2 Governance Capture\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The alternative \u8212- governance voting \u8212- creates different problems:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whale capture (large token holders control decisions)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Voter apathy (most holders don\u8217't vote)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Political coordination costs (proposals, lobbying, campaigning)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Slow iteration (everything goes through proposal/vote/timelock)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 1.3 The Third Option\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 What if forks were {\b features, not threats?} What if every fork automatically maintained an economic relationship with its parent? What if convergence was incentivized but divergence was permitted?\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 2. Fork Protocol Design\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 2.1 Fork Registration\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Any address can fork VibeSwap by deploying a new instance and registering it with the {\f1 ForkRegistry.sol} contract:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 ForkRegistry.registerFork(\line
    parentId,           // Which instance this forks from\line
    forkAddress,        // Deployed fork contract address\line
    feeSplitBps,        // Fee split (default: 5000 = 50%)\line
    stateSnapshotHash   // Hash of parent state at fork point\line
)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Registration is permissionless. No governance vote required. The fork immediately begins operating independently.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 2.2 Fee Split Mechanism\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Every fork implements a {\f1 FeeRouter} that splits protocol fees:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 Total fees generated by fork\line
    \u9474 ?\line
    \u9500 ?\u9472 ?\u9472 ? 50% \u8594 ? Fork treasury (fork keeps)\line
    \u9474 ?\line
    \u9492 ?\u9472 ?\u9472 ? 50% \u8594 ? Parent treasury (routes back)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is enforced at the smart contract level, not by social agreement. The fork contract inherits the fee router from the parent. Removing it requires a code change that is visible on-chain and detectable by the parent.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 2.3 Recursive Fee Flow\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Forks can fork other forks. Fee splits compound:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 VibeSwap (root)\line
    \u9474 ?\line
    \u9500 ?\u9472 ?\u9472 ? Fork A (50% of Fork A's fees \u8594 ? root)\line
    \u9474 ?       \u9474 ?\line
    \u9474 ?       \u9492 ?\u9472 ?\u9472 ? Fork A1 (50% of A1's fees \u8594 ? Fork A)\line
    \u9474 ?              \u8594 ? Fork A gets 50% of A1\line
    \u9474 ?              \u8594 ? Root gets 50% of Fork A (which includes 25% of A1)\line
    \u9474 ?\line
    \u9492 ?\u9472 ?\u9472 ? Fork B (50% of Fork B's fees \u8594 ? root)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 At depth d, the root receives {\f1 1/2^d} of each descendant\u8217's fees. This creates a power-law distribution where the root benefits from all activity in the network, with diminishing returns at each depth level.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Total root revenue from a fully active fork tree of depth D:}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 R_root = SUM(d=1 to D) of [N_d \u215 ? F_d \u215 ? (1/2)^d]\line
\line
Where:\line
  N_d = number of forks at depth d\line
  F_d = average fees per fork at depth d\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 2.4 Fork State\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each fork maintains: - Its own liquidity pools (can differ from parent) - Its own batch auction parameters (can tune timing) - Its own frontend and branding - Its own governance (if any, subject to decay) - Automatic fee routing back to parent chain\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 What a fork CANNOT change: - The fee split ratio (hardcoded at registration) - The fee routing smart contract (inherited, immutable) - The Shapley distribution mechanism (core invariant)\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 3. Economic Gravity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 3.1 Why Malicious Forks Starve\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A fork that exists purely to extract value (e.g., removes MEV protection, adds hidden fees) will:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Lose users to the parent (which has better protections)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Generate minimal fees (no volume = no revenue)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Still route 50% of its minimal fees to the parent\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Net result: fork costs more to operate than it earns\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The economic gravity toward the root is natural. You can fork VibeSwap, but you can\u8217't fork its users, reputation, or liquidity network effects.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 3.2 Why Aligned Forks Thrive\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A fork that innovates (e.g., adds new trading pairs, deploys on a new chain, implements a novel mechanism) will:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Attract users who want the innovation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Generate fees proportional to its volume\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Route 50% back to the parent (contributing to root ecosystem)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Receive network effects from root ecosystem (shared reputation, cross-fork liquidity)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The fork benefits the root, and the root\u8217's strength benefits the fork.} This is positive-sum forking.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 3.3 The Black Hole Metaphor\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In astrophysics, a black hole\u8217's gravitational pull increases with mass. In the fork network, the root protocol\u8217's economic pull increases with the total fee flow from all forks. More forks \u8594 ? more fee flow \u8594 ? stronger root \u8594 ? more attractive to fork from \u8594 ? more forks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is a self-reinforcing cycle that makes the root protocol increasingly dominant over time, without any governance mechanism or legal enforcement.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 4. Reconvergence\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 4.1 When Forks Should Merge\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A fork that has evolved independently but remains aligned with the parent should be able to merge back. Reasons to reconverge:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Fork\u8217's innovation has been adopted by parent (no more differentiation)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Fork\u8217's user base overlaps significantly with parent\u8217's\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Separate operation creates unnecessary liquidity fragmentation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Fork community votes to rejoin (or fork\u8217's governance decays to zero)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 4.2 Reconvergence Conditions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A fork can propose reconvergence if:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab {\b State hash alignment}: Fork\u8217's core state variables (pool parameters, fee structure, governance rules) match parent\u8217's within a tolerance threshold\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab {\b N-block consistency}: State hashes have matched for N consecutive blocks (proving sustained alignment, not temporary coincidence)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab {\b Mutual consent}: Both fork and parent governance (or automated controllers) approve the merge\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 4.3 Merge Process\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 1. Fork proposes reconvergence \u8594 ? ForkRegistry.proposeReconvergence(forkId)\line
2. State hash comparison over N blocks\line
3. If aligned: merge liquidity pools (combined depth)\line
4. Accumulated fork treasury fees distributed to fork contributors\line
5. Fork's Shapley history merges into parent's ContributionDAG\line
6. Fork contract self-destructs, redirecting all traffic to parent\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 4.4 Merged Fee Distribution\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On reconvergence, the fork\u8217's accumulated treasury (the 50% it kept) is distributed: - Fork LPs: proportional to their liquidity contribution - Fork contributors: proportional to their Shapley values - Parent treasury: small integration fee (1-5%)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This creates a positive terminal event for fork participants \u8212- they don\u8217't lose value by reconverging.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 5. Directed Acyclic Graph Topology\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 5.1 Structure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The fork network forms a DAG (directed acyclic graph), not a tree. Forks can reference multiple parents (multi-fork) and can exist at any depth.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1     VibeSwap (root)\line
      /     \\\line
   Fork A   Fork B\line
     |    \\   /\line
   Fork A1  Fork AB  (forks both A and B)\line
     |\line
   Fork A1a\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 5.2 Multi-Fork Fee Routing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A fork with multiple parents splits its parent-bound fees proportionally:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 Fork AB fees:\line
  50% \u8594 ? Fork AB keeps\line
  25% \u8594 ? Fork A (parent 1)\line
  25% \u8594 ? Fork B (parent 2)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each parent then routes its portion up the tree normally.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 5.3 Asynchronous Updates\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each fork operates on its own schedule: - Own batch auction timing (could be 5s, 10s, 30s) - Own chain deployment (Base, Arbitrum, CKB, etc.) - Own upgrade schedule (not blocked by parent governance) - Own liquidity depth (independent market making)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Coherence emerges from economic alignment, not forced synchronization. Forks that diverge too far lose users. Forks that stay aligned accumulate users. The economics do the governing.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 6. Governance Implications\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 6.1 Forks as Governance Escape Valve\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The fork network eliminates contentious governance forever. If a minority disagrees with a majority decision:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab They fork (permissionless, instant)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab They implement their preferred parameters\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab They compete for users on merit\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Fee split ensures both versions benefit from each other\u8217's success\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 No drama. No politics. No DAO votes at 3am. Fork and prove your thesis with users.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 6.2 Governance Minimization\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 With the fork escape valve, governance scope shrinks to: - Dispute resolution (slashing adjudication) - Emergency pauses (circuit breaker activation) - Parameter boundary enforcement (preventing obviously destructive settings)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Everything else \u8212- fee rates, pool parameters, mechanism tweaks \u8212- is decided by the market. Fork if you disagree, and let users choose.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 6.3 Ungovernance Compatibility\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The fork network accelerates the Ungovernance time bomb. As governance power decays, the fork mechanism becomes the primary adaptation pathway. The protocol evolves through natural selection of forks, not through political governance.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 7. Implementation Roadmap\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Phase 1: Fork Registry (Q2 2026)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Deploy {\f1 ForkRegistry.sol} with registration and fee routing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Implement {\f1 FeeRouter.sol} with hardcoded 50/50 split\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Build fork explorer UI showing tree topology and fee flows\sa180\par}
